         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Colonial Botanists Office ¶ William Street ¶ Brisbane ¶ April 7th 1890 ¶ My dear Baron...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">90.04.07</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Frederick Bailey</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M5, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Exocarya sclerioides</seg> (MEL 2199564). Attached to the sheet are a later Queensland Herbarium label 'Exocarya sclerioides <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">Benth</hi>
                     </seg> | Co-type of <name key="Scleria%20ustulata">Scleria ustulata</name>
                     <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">F. M Bailey</hi>
                     </seg>', <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and Bailey's note 'Inclosed find Sample of the Southern Plant F.M.B.'. Bailey described it as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Scleria%20ustulata">Scleria ustulata</name>
                     </seg> in Bailey (1890), p. 81.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0.1598in; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotations by M: 'Answ 14/6/90' [letter not found] and 'Exocarya scleroides, Bentham’.</p>
               </note>Colonial Botanists Office</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">William Street</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Brisbane</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">April 7th 1890</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>So far as I am able to make out; the Sedge no […]<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Space left blank in MS.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> is a new species of Scleria, and I purpose describing it under the name of S. ustulata or something similar on account of the scorched appearance of the spikelets. I only met with it on the Bellenden Ker Range at an altitude of 4-to-5,000 ft. but it is evidently identical with one which was sent to me by a correspondent on the Tweed River<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">i. e. Mr T. Steel, who is listed as the collector on the labels on the specimen from the Tweed River, BRI-AQ341588.</p>
               </note> some 5 to 6 years ago — but as you know I only wish to attend to the Queensland flora I took no steps to describe it as a new species at the time. Even, now, you my<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">may?</p>
               </note> think me presumptuous to name a fresh species of a genus containing over one hundred species when not half of these have I<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">a?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> description however our plants must be named even at the risk of now and again a mistake being made you will I am sure agree with me thus far.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My friend Dr Chas. Prentice points out to me that the new <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Dimeria%20glabrescens">Dimeria glabrescens</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> had better be changed to D. glabiuscula which I shall do. I am much afraid that several of the large fruit bearing trees of the district will have to waite determination until I receive flowering specimens. when I forwarded specimens of them to you I was in hopes that your collector Sayers<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">W.A. Sayer.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> might have furnished you with the flowering portions, in going over them if I can make them out however I will at once let you know as now the results.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">yours very truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>F. M. Bailey</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Inclosed find Sample of the Southern Plant</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">F.M.B.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dimeria%20glabrescens">Dimeria glabrescens</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dimeria%20glabiuscula">Dimeria glabiuscula</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Scleria%20ustulata">Scleria ustulata</name>
            </p>
         </div>
